fields.name: NOA Restaurant
fields.description:
NOA IS AS OPEN-MINDED AND INTERNATIONAL, AS IT IS AIRY. ULTIMATELY IT’S OUR CLIENTELE WHO CREATE THE ATMOSPHERE FILLING OUR BEACH HOUSE.
AND THE FOOD… TASTE PALETTE, THAT IS INSPIRED BY OUR TRAVELS AROUND THE WORLD. NATURAL, LIKE THE MATERIALS USED FOR NOA’S COSY YET ECLECTIC INTERIOR.

fields.name: Restaurant Argentina
fields.description:
Argentiina, this means love and passion for grilled meat – un amor y pasión por el asado. ¡Olé!

Asado is an emotion, a story about happiness, passion, and love – just like tango argentine danced at night on the streets of Buenos Aires. However, if tango is simply hot, asado is fiery, even more spicy and sizzling. And of course Buenos Aires itself – impatiently glimmering megacity with its streets filled with delicious grilling aroma. The wandering smoky scent pulls you in and makes every justification for the suave name of the restless metropolis: Buenos Aires – “Good Air”.

fields.name: Sigmund Freud Bar
fields.description: Cocktail bar in Old Tallinn. ...сome to us for everything you needed. Come to us when you don’t know what we needed, hoping someone might tell us. Come to us when looking for love, or sex, or trouble, or for someone who had gone missing, because sooner or later everyone turn up there...

fields.name: Whisper Sister
fields.description: Speakeasy-style bar, hidden in the heart of Tallinn. Inspired by the world's best classic cocktail bars.

fields.name: Kumu
fields.description: The Kumu Art Museum is an art museum in Tallinn, Estonia. It is one of the largest museums in Estonia and one of the largest art museums in Northern Europe. It is one of the five branches of the Art Museum of Estonia, housing its main offices. Kumu is an abbreviation of the Estonian "Kunstimuuseum".

fields.name: Lennusadam
fields.description: The Seaplane Harbour is a maritime museum in Tallinn, Estonia, opened in spring 2012. The museum is part of the Estonian Maritime Museum. The museum is located in the Tallinn aeroplane harbour in a building originally constructed as a hangar for seaplanes in the area of Peter the Great's Naval Fortress.
